06692nam a22007095i 9780822384816DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223848167 a10.1515/97808223848162doi  a(DE-B1597)552499  a(OCoLC)1055303382  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPOL0000002bisacsh00aCommunities of the Air :bRadio Century, Radio Culture /ced. by Susan Merrill Squier. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tCommunities of the Air: Introducing the Radio World -- tRadio Technology across the Twentieth Century -- tAT&T Invents Public Access Broadcasting in 1923: A Foreclosed Model for American Radio -- tCompromising Technologies: Government, the Radio Hobby, and the Discourse of Catastrophe in the Twentieth Century -- tA Promise Diminished: The Politics of Low- Power Radio -- tRadio Cultures -- tCaribbean Voices on the Air: Radio, Poetry, and Nationalism in the Anglophone Caribbean -- tThe Forgotten Fifteen Million: Black Radio, Radicalism, and the Construction of the ‘‘Negro Market’’ -- tPackaged Alternatives: The Incorporation and Gendering of ‘‘Alternative’’ Radio -- tScience Literacies: The Mandate and Complicity of Popular Science on the Radio -- tNot Hearing Poetry on Public Radio -- tRadio Ideologies -- tIn the Radio Way: Elizabeth II, the Female Voice-Over, and the Radio’s Imperial Effects -- tIf the Country’s Going Gracie, So Can You’’: Gender Representation in Gracie Allen’s Radio Comedy -- t‘‘Are You Lonesome Tonight?’’: Gendered Address in The Lonesome Gal and The Continental -- tWireless Possibilities, Posthuman Possibilities: Brain Radio, Community Radio, Radio Lazarus -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA pioneering analysis of radio as both a cultural and material production, Communities of the Air explores radio’s powerful role in shaping Anglo-American culture and society since the early twentieth century. Scholars and radio writers, producers, and critics look at the many ways radio generates multiple communities over the air—from elite to popular, dominant to resistant, canonical to transgressive. The contributors approach radio not only in its own right, but also as a set of practices—both technological and social—illuminating broader issues such as race relations, gender politics, and the construction of regional and national identities.Drawing on the perspectives of literary and cultural studies, science studies and feminist theory, radio history, and the new field of radio studies, these essays consider the development of radio as technology: how it was modeled on the telephone, early conflicts between for-profit and public uses of radio, and amateur radio (HAMS), local programming, and low-power radio. Some pieces discuss how radio gives voice to different cultural groups, focusing on the BBC and poetry programming in the West Indies, black radio, the history of alternative radio since the 1970s, and science and contemporary arts programming. Others look at radio’s influence on gender (and gender’s influence on radio) through examinations of Queen Elizabeth’s broadcasts, Gracie Allen’s comedy, and programming geared toward women. Together the contributors demonstrate how attention to the variety of ways radio is used and understood reveals the dynamic emergence and transformation of communities within the larger society.Contributors. Laurence A. Breiner, Bruce B. Campbell, Mary Desjardins, Lauren M. E. Goodlad, Nina Hunteman, Leah Lowe, Adrienne Munich, Kathleen Newman, Martin Spinelli, Susan Merrill Squier, Donald Ulin, Mark Williams, Steve Wurzler  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on onl